    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>Overhauling Health Care</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Dr Kenneth E Smith letter responds to June 11 front-page article on Massachusetts referendum on patients' bill of rights; asserts patients should be placed above profits in health care system</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>It is not surprising that the citizens of Massachusetts have decided to take matters to the ballot box since patients' bills of rights have been stymied in committee at both the federal and state levels (front page, June 11).  The frustrations of doctors, nurses, mental health care professionals, social workers, administrators and patients continue to be voiced in meetings of organizations like the Ad Hoc Committee to Defend Health Care.</p>
        <p>These frustrations will most likely lead to a favorable vote in November despite the opposition's spending millions of our health care premium dollars to try to defeat the initiative.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>It is not surprising that the citizens of Massachusetts have decided to take matters to the ballot box since patients' bills of rights have been stymied in committee at both the federal and state levels (front page, June 11).  The frustrations of doctors, nurses, mental health care professionals, social workers, administrators and patients continue to be voiced in meetings of organizations like the Ad Hoc Committee to Defend Health Care.</p>
        <p>These frustrations will most likely lead to a favorable vote in November despite the opposition's spending millions of our health care premium dollars to try to defeat the initiative.</p>
        <p>There is a way to solve the many problems in our health care system: by placing patients above profits.</p>
        <p>KENNETH E. SMITH, M.D.  Hyannis, Mass., June 11, 2000</p>
      </block>
